{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"84408817-3b1c-424e-a23e-8c6f74ab344a","content":"The working directory is empty, so I'll answer from general knowledge.\n\nOn macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes and `createdump` isn't available (it's not shipped with NativeAOT apps), you can recover the crash dump using the **OS-native mechanism**:\n\n1. **Check for Apple crash reports** — macOS automatically writes `.ips` / `.crash` files to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for a file matching your process name and crash timestamp.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** via the shell before running your app:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Core files are written to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Check SIP** — System Integrity Protection can prevent core dump generation. Verify with:\n   ```bash\n   csrutil status\n   ```\n   If enabled, core dumps may only be written for processes in certain locations.\n\n4. **Analyze the dump** — Once you have a core file, open it with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **For richer .NET diagnostics**, set these environment variables *before* the crash:\n   ```bash\n   export DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\n   export DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4   # full dump\n   export DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/coredump.%p\n   ```\n   However, these rely on the CoreCLR crash handler, which NativeAOT does **not** include — so for NativeAOT, the `ulimit -c unlimited` + `/cores/` approach (steps 2–4) is your primary path.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"359defb8-83e1-4c95-ae67-de14314362c9","outputTokens":444,"requestId":"9818:81F2F:79F20F2:869A84C:69F406D0"},"id":"77373f5d-966a-4f8c-bcf5-531731df8369","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:50:19.493Z","parentId":"a21c2311-b1f5-41ca-92d7-09ad030b5a8a"}
